The MICHELIN Guide makes you discover the diversity of Zagreb's culinary scene and its rich cuisine built around exceptional local products. We stop at @res_tac_ where we meet chef @miletic_v, her gardener and her producers coming from Zagreb County. The men show us their wonderful range of local products (goat cheese, wine and honey) and share their specific attributes with us.
 
On the threshold between East and West, Zagreb and its county offer a rich and stunning gastronomic scene embodied by talented chefs who are devoted to highlighting the quality of the local ingredients. In a residential district outside the city centre, chef Vesna Miletic prepares Mediterranean-influenced dishes composed of fresh product directly coming from the city markets and her local producers. Let's discover a female chef, her producers and their product which make the gastronomic reputation of this stunning capital city!
 
Cosmopolitan buzz of @zagrebtourist and @visitzagrebcounty may strike you.
 
📍 Zagreb, Croatia . .

The MICHELIN Guide takes you to Zagreb to discover the treasures of the capital city of Croatia, their chefs, their products and their producers. We take a closer look at the establishment @esplanadezagreb where Chef @anagrgicchef runs the kitchen of two restaurants Zinfandel's and Le Bistro Esplanade – both distinguished with a Plate in the MICHELIN Guide Croatia 2020.
 
On the threshold between East and West, Zagreb and its county offer a rich and stunning gastronomic scene marrying culinary influences from continental and Mediterranean countries. Among the restaurants of the city, two are housed in Esplanade hotel considered as one of the capital's most popular places for eating. While the French classic Bistro is a smartly dressed yet informal all-day place, the luxurious Zinfandel's restaurant effortlessly combines the elegance of a bygone era with the ambience of a contemporary dining room. Chef Ana Grgić Tomić prepares ambitious menus offering Croatian classics, like strukli, alongside modern European dishes.
 
Cosmopolitan buzz of @zagrebtourist and @visitzagrebcounty may strike you.
 
📍 Zagreb, Croatia

To celebrate International Sustainable Gastronomy Day, chefs and heads  of restaurants awarded a MICHELIN Green Star are sharing some recipes with us that help make the world a little greener!
 
Today, it’s Chef @dominiquecrenn’s turn. At the head of three-MICHELIN-Starred @atelier.crenn in San Francisco, she chips in with this offering that is a  great way to eat up all those perfect summer tomatoes. Today’s recipe is for juicy, simple confit and marinated tomato salad – one of her favorite ways to enjoy this simple pleasure!
 
Yield: 4

Thanks for the recipe, Chef Dominique Crenn! 

Share your version with us 👉Tag @michelinguideand use #MICHELINGUIDEATHOME

node.title: MICHELIN Guide At Home - Dominique Crenn’s Tomato Salad

node.text:
To celebrate International Sustainable Gastronomy Day, chefs at the head of restaurants awarded a MICHELIN Green Star are sharing some recipes that help make the world a little greener!
 
To @massimobottura, it’s essential to “never let food go to waste.” The Chef of Three-MICHELIN-Starred Osteria Francescana shares this message of hope and goodwill in the form of his grandmother’s recipe for traditional Passatelli. In this recipe, the star of the show are humble breadcrumbs, which are for him the epitome of the “waste not, want not” food ethic.
 
Thanks for the recipe, Chef Massimo Bottura! 

Illustrations by @alice.vdw 
Share your version with us 👉Tag @michelinguide and use #MICHELINGUIDEATHOME

Today we celebrate International Sustainable Gastronomy Day with chefs and foodies around the world. 

We’re kicking it off with this amazing recipe for herb butter artichoke tacos handed to us from Chef Gary Yin, who helms restaurant King’s Joy in Beijing, 3 stars and a MICHELIN Green star in the MICHELIN China Guide 2021. 
 
Celebrate with us by making the recipe at home and share the results in your story tagging @MICHELINGUIDE and @legengaryin!
 
Serves: 4, 3 tacos per pax

Tip from the chef: You can crack fresh black pepper and/or a few drops of Tabasco for more pop!

Thanks for the recipe, Chef Gary Yin! 

Share your version with us 👉Tag @michelinguide and use #MICHELINGUIDEATHOME

Our Inspectors say, "The name Tsukimi references the mid-autumn harvest festival honoring the moon at its fullest and brightest. With that seasonal approach in mind, Chef Takanori Akiyama has created a deeply personal interpretation of a proper kaiseki meal. 

Thanks to our partner @wineaccess! #wineaccess

See the entire MICHELIN Guide New York selection for 2021 at https://bit.ly/3tL6PYT
and stay tuned for more of the 2021 MICHELIN Guide announcements.

Awarded a MICHELIN Green Star, the establishment @ristorantevirtuosogourmet pays tribute to Tuscany, thanks to its chef @sardi_antonello who showcases modern culinary techniques. The project of Virtuoso Gourmet began in 2014 with sustainability as its key concept. Ruins dating from the 18C have been carefully restored to house a geothermal heating system to produce renewable energy, creating a perfect harmony with the Tuscan environment surrounding the property.

At Virtuoso Gourmet, the chef pays tribute to the products of the property's garden and farm where farmyard animals are raised. In this certified organic property, the team takes passionately care of six hectares where we can find century-old fruits, olive trees or a newly planted vineyard. If the produce can not be sourced from the farmland, the local farmers with whom the chef has forged strong links provide what he needs to cook.

“Our commitment to the pursuit of a sustainable philosophy in all aspects of the business is an ongoing incentive.”

Swipe right to check out the chef’s culinary commitments!

📍 San Piero a Sieve, Italy

Illustration by @alice.vdw
📷 Stefano Borghesi

Chef @massimobottura remains a singular culinary talent acclaimed across the globe, and his cuisine at The Osteria Francescana remains focused on innovative touches to traditional recipes from Emilia region in Italy.
However, the philosophy of the restaurant that was awarded a MICHELIN Green Star goes beyond culinary innovation; it is also committed to implement sustainable initiatives in the daily life. For him, sustainability is not only about ecology but also social progress; Bottura's team aims to fight food waste but also to encourage social inclusion.

node.text:
Stop in the warm Mediterranean sun in Saint-Tropez! At @restaurant_colette_sainttropez, Chef Philippe Colinet, technically sound, creates stripped-back cuisine that pays a tribute to Mediterranean flavours and vegetables.

🍴 Seaweed and vegetables

📍 Saint-Tropez, France
.
📷 Repost Restaurant Colette

#MICHELINrestaurants #restaurants #gastronomy #foodies #foodiegram #instafood #seaweed #finedining #OneMICHELINStar #GuideMICHELINFR

Today's recipe is for a Spanish dish inspired of Ajoblanco of Sardine, but much more complex. Born in the imagination of the chef, this “Sardine and Sardajo” dish mixes different textures: crunchy sardine paired with a touch of eggplant puree and fish broth flavored with citrus notes.
Begoña Rodrigo, chef at @lasalita_rte – awarded 1 Star in the MICHELIN Guide Spain and Portugal 2021 – shares the secrets of preparation of her Sardine and Sardajo.
 
Measurement equivalents:
40g =1.4 oz
75g= 2.6 oz
50g= 1.7 oz
80g= 2.8 oz
3g= 1 teaspoon
Servings: 10

Tip from the chef: to bring more flavours to the dish, you can make smoked butter.

Thanks for the recipe @begorodrigo_!

Illustrations by @alice.vdw
📸 La Salita

Have you tried a good old Thai-style coconut ice cream? Yummy either on its own, with crispy cones, or some traditional soft and fluffy bread. Chef @chaleekader of 100 Mahaseth in Bangkok has elevated regular ice cream to the next level. The extra-rich brioche keeps its shape even when topped with icy cold ice cream. The coconut is served with sweetened pumpkin slices, sticky rice, and roasted cashew nuts. Salted egg yolk is grated and sprinkled over à la minute to add the extra kick. Be sure to get everything in one bite!

🍴 Thai-style coconut ice cream

The MICHELIN Guide makes you discover the diversity of Zagreb's culinary scene and its rich cuisine built around exceptional local products. We stop at @res_tac_ where we meet chef @miletic_v, her gardener and her producers coming from Zagreb County. The men show us their wonderful range of local products (goat cheese, wine and honey) and share their specific attributes with us.
 
On the threshold between East and West, Zagreb and its county offer a rich and stunning gastronomic scene embodied by talented chefs who are devoted to highlighting the quality of the local ingredients. In a residential district outside the city centre, chef Vesna Miletic prepares Mediterranean-influenced dishes composed of fresh product directly coming from the city markets and her local producers. Let's discover a female chef, her producers and their product which make the gastronomic reputation of this stunning capital city!
 
Cosmopolitan buzz of @zagrebtourist and @visitzagrebcounty may strike you.
 
📍 Zagreb, Croatia . .
#MICHELINFoodTravel #MICHELINrestaurants #chef #gastronomy #MICHELINstar20 #MICHELINGuideCR

@cheflaurentpetit is thriving in Annecy-le-Vieux, France, at @closdessens – awarded a MICHELIN Green Star – where he devises “lake cuisine” of an exceptionally high standard. On the menu, meat has been replaced by organic fish from the surrounding lakes and is elevated to culinary greatness.

The cooks-gardeners are involved in the 500m2 of vegetable, aromatic and fruit gardens, all managed in line with permaculture philosophy. Except possibly for certain varieties and only in summer, Le Clos des Sens is not self-sufficient as the team wishes to maintain their relationship with their producers. The wealth of produce from local and committed producers with whom the chef works also contributes to its flavours.

Whether by implementing intelligent waste recycling or collecting and reusing rainwater, Chef Petit strives to bring common sense to the entire life of the restaurant.

"This nature, this environment, this garden, it's endless. I'm even thinking of proposing customers to eat salad with their fingers. This allows us to be in harmony with our nourishing earth."

📍 Annecy, France

📷 Matthieu Cellard

Illustration by @alice.vdw

Today’s recipe is dedicated to a flavorful Mexican appetizer: Aguachile! Composed of tuna “cooked”  in lime juice, this bright and refreshing dish takes it a step further by adding jalapeño and watermelon juice, giving it this rosé color and spicy deliciousness!
Val Cantu, chef-owner of @californiossf – 2 Stars in the MICHELIN Guide San Francisco 2021 – shares the secrets of fabrication of his summer version of watermelon aguachile.

420g= 1¼ cup

Tip of the chef: “This recipe can be made very easily with any sashimi-quality fish.”

We take you on a virtual visit to some of the most extraordinary-decorated establishments in the MICHELIN Guide selection. Today, it's the turn of MICHELIN Plate awarded restaurant @kodawariramen.
 
You don't have to travel to Tokyo to feel like you're in the Land of the Rising Sun. The bustling vibe and narrow dimensions of this restaurant located in Paris are reminiscent of an eatery in historic Tokyo. Everything gives us the feeling of being in a Yokocho with the decoration and its unavoidable gadgets coming directly from Japan. Surprisingly enough, a soundtrack of Tokyo street ambience runs in loop inside the restaurant.
 
Behind this true temple dedicated to Ramen, stands a former fighter pilot and airline pilot, Jean-Baptiste Meusnier; who has an overwhelming passion for Japanese culture and especially for its gastronomy, Ramen. There, the ramen made on site and served in delicious broths of Landes poultry, attract not only Japanese culture enthusiasts, but gourmets from every horizon.

📍 Paris, France
